uake: The Great Kantō Earthquake and Taishō Japan -- t15. Alan Tansman, The Aesthetics of Japanese Fascism -- t16. Japanese Literature as a Modern Invention: a review of Haruo Shirane and Tomi Suzuki (eds.), Inventing the Classics: Modernity, National Identity, and Japanese Literature -- t17. Haruo Shirane, Japan and the Culture of the Four Seasons: Nature, Literature, and the Arts -- t18. Steven Heine and Dale S. Wright (eds.), Zen Masters -- tBibliography of Roy Starrs Publications -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJapan is widely regarded as having a unique culture and a strong national identity. Paradoxically, however, many basic elements of Japanese culture are not originally Japanese. Since the beginning of its history, Japan has been one of the world’s major importers of foreign cultures. Its culture was thoroughly "hybrid" long before that word became fashionable in contemporary global studies. But this does not mean that Japan’s culture lacks originality. The Japanese have always made strikingly original contributions, even improvements, to whatever they imported. Even more significantly, the "hybridity" of their culture produced ongoing tensions that served as a kind of creative dynamo for Japanese writers, artists, and intellectuals. This book explores the fundamental creative tension between the native and the foreign in many areas of Japanese culture, from politics and religion to art and literature – a tension also often interpreted as between tradition and modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGroup identityzJapan. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary History. 4aContemporary Society. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticis